metadata.name: Illuminations #53
metadata.description:
Created for the FxHash Turns One week - Thank you FxHash for all the opportunities you have given generative artists and collectors, and thank you to everyone who makes, and collects, the great art here. Here are a few celebratory generative effects which come from my 2022 experiments on random walks through color and space.

There are 5 different burst patterns (Whirligig, Sky Ripple, Confetti, Classic, Sparkler) and the Cocktail type brings them all together (somewhat chaotically)

To continue with the display after it stops press c

To switch to tranquil mode press t - You will want to try this out when you have a minute

To switch back to live mode press v

To stop the display process press x

To save a 2800x2800 jpg press s

Made with p5.js - all proceeds and royalties assigned to the Processing Foundation (who also deserve a big thank you)

metadata.name: Starmap - AI Study I #97
metadata.description:
Starmap brings you to different sectors of the generative art galaxy. A first of its kind generative art experiment using a Text2Code workflow, which involves writing text prompts that get translated into javascript code. This project was created with English words and human imagination, but the programming of the piece is all AI.

The code for this project was written entirely by AI using GPT-3. None of the code was altered or created by a human aside from changing some Math.random() with fxrand().

Text2Code study #1 /// Project CoDexter by @BrainArtLabs

metadata.name: The seed :: issue 1 #42
metadata.description:
*the seed* is an experimental project, meaning that we give ourselves permission to test the waters and see where the current takes us. *the seed* is also a zine, which suggests something both unpretentious and grassroots — it's most definitely a labor of love!

The first issue is on the minimalist side, with a total of 19 pages nonetheless! We avoided big blocks of text and leaned into finding creative solutions to allow the artists to express themselves without having to produce new work. We also elected not to systematically showcase an artist's latest project as a way of jumping off the cultural treadmill which has conditioned us to focus almost exclusively on "what's new" and "what's next". As a result, *the seed*, which we envisage as a quarterly publication, will hopefully convey a certain quality of timelessness.

This issue is a collective invitation to catch our breath and celebrate the beauty that has been brought forth by a diverse group of amazing artists from all over the world: Lammetje, Liam Egan, Ciput, Elsif & Clint Fulkerson. Instead of asking the typical interview questions, we invited each artist to introduce themselves using a text based recording device which allows the reader to witness the workings of the artist's mind. The result feels both lighthearted and intimate.

The edition size is 128 and statistically one in five coverpages will be an animated collage created using the artwork of one of our five artists. No two coverpages are alike as the seed differs for each collage. This might be less apparent if the project is only examined through thumbnails. Please take the time to explore all of the interactive features of *the seed* on full screen.

*the seed* was made with C++ and OpenGL and converted to the web via Emscripten.

Thank you for reading this metadata and for coming on this journey with us!

metadata.name: Artverse Cube Pass #17
metadata.description:
The Artverse Cube Pass is the first collection that provides value inside the Artverse. For background information on the Artverse, see the fxtext article The Artverse (https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/the-artverse).

This pass, the Cube Pass, gives you ownership of a Cube, and the ability to customize a Cube. Owning a Cube Pass is the first step into the Artverse. Cubes have many uses, one being a place to showcase art, like a gallery. Customizing a Cube is fast and flexible.

See the accompanying fxtext article The Artverse Cube Pass (https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/the-artverse-cube-pass) for more information.

Using Your Cube in the Artverse

After minting your Cube Pass, go to the Artverse at https://artverse.place and start configuring your Cube!

Interaction

Cubes are built with Babylonjs and are fully interactive. Click the Help button to see how to navigate inside a Cube. Most objects in a Cube, like the Billboards, Frames, and Portals can be clicked for fast and accurate navigation. For example, clicking a Billboard will position the camera directly in front of the Billboard for fast viewing.

The Art in the Cube Pass

The Cube Pass has value in the Artverse, but it also has value as a unique artwork.

The art displayed in your particular iteration of the Cube Pass uses some ai assisted art created with the best ai tools currently available. We have created a large number of amazing images, many of which could have value on their own, separate from the Cube Pass. There are over 150 images, and each iteration uses a unique subset of these images in the Frames and Billboards of your Cube. I hope you enjoy them.

Rarities

2% chance of getting a Private Space Pass, along with the Cube Pass.
1% chance of getting an All Access Pass. This will allow access to all features of the Artverse now and into the future.

See the accompanying fxtext article The Artverse Cube Pass (https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/the-artverse-cube-pass) for more information about these other passes.

Keyboard

'p' creates a png of the current view. The png will be the exact size of the current window.
'h' toggles the hud that shows how to naviage in a Cube.

metadata.name: CityScape: Istanbul #48
metadata.description:
Istanbul is a city that straddles the Bosporus Strait, and lies in both Europe and Asia, with a population of over 15 million residents. Most of the population is located in big iconic hills known as the "Seven Hills of Istanbul". 

   In this project, I tried to capture and interpret the daily life routine of the people who live in these hills with the viewing point from Bosphorus. There are three camera angle possibilities to examine the details in different layers. Also, building types, the slope of the hill, and green area density vary in between those scenarios. There are two time zones: day and night. In the night scene, there is a possibility to obtain the crescent moon which is the symbol of the culture inhabits in these lands.

To save as a high-quality image, open in live view and click yes on the incoming prompt.

Created with p5js
